{"id":"2106.13582","submitter":"Alejandro Kievsky","authors":"A. Kievsky, G. Orlandini, M. Gattobigio","title":"A Many-Body Density Energy Functional","comments":"7 pages and 2 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 104, 030801 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.104.L030801","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th cond-mat.quant-gas","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Hohenberg-Kohn theorem and the Kohn-Sham equations, which are at the\nbasis of the Density Functional Theory, are reformulated in terms of a\nparticular many-body density, which is translational invariant and therefore is\nrelevant for self-bound systems. In a similar way that there is a unique\nrelation between the one-body density and the external potential that gives\nrise to it, we demonstrate that there is a unique relation between that\nparticular many-body density and a definite many-body potential. The energy is\nthen a functional of this density and its minimization leads to the\nground-state energy of the system. As a proof of principle, the analogous of\nthe Kohn-Sham equation is solved in the specific case of $^4$He atomic\nclusters, to put in evidence the advantages of this new formulation in terms of\nphysical insights.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 24 Jun 2021 14:02:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-09-29"}
{"id":"2106.13583","submitter":"Manuel Schneider","authors":"Manuel Schneider, Johann Ostmeyer, Karl Jansen, Thomas Luu, Carsten\n  Urbach","title":"Simulating both parity sectors of the Hubbard Model with Tensor Networks","comments":"20 pages, 20 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 104 (2021) 155118","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.104.155118","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.comp-ph cond-mat.str-el hep-lat","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Tensor networks are a powerful tool to simulate a variety of different\nphysical models, including those that suffer from the sign problem in Monte\nCarlo simulations. The Hubbard model on the honeycomb lattice with non-zero\nchemical potential is one such problem. Our method is based on projected\nentangled pair states (PEPS) using imaginary time evolution. We demonstrate\nthat it provides accurate estimators for the ground state of the model,\nincluding cases where Monte Carlo simulations fail miserably. In particular it\nshows near to optimal, that is linear, scaling in lattice size. We also present\na novel approach to directly simulate the subspace with an odd number of\nfermions. It allows to independently determine the ground state in both\nsectors. Without a chemical potential this corresponds to half filling and the\nlowest energy state with one additional electron or hole. We identify several\nstability issues, such as degenerate ground states and large single particle\ngaps, and provide possible fixes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 24 Jun 2021 14:48:02 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 2 Jul 2021 12:10:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-10-13"}
